Create a full end-to-end integration test for the magic link authentication flow. This test proves the entire auth pipeline works through Docker infrastructure.

Note: The auth SERVICE (Snapp.Service.Auth) may not be fully implemented yet from Sprint 1 — if so, create the test as a specification that will pass once the service is built. But if there is enough service code to test against, wire it up.

Create `test/Snapp.Service.Auth.Tests/AuthFlowIntegrationTests.cs`:

Use the DockerTestFixture from Snapp.TestHelpers.

```csharp
[Collection("DockerInfrastructure")]
public class AuthFlowIntegrationTests
{
    // Test 1: Full magic link flow
    // 1. POST /api/auth/magic-link with email
    // 2. Assert: 200 response
    // 3. Query Papercut for the email
    // 4. Extract magic link code from email body
    // 5. POST /api/auth/validate with code
    // 6. Assert: 200 with JWT + refresh token
    // 7. Decode JWT, verify claims (sub, exp, iss)

    // Test 2: Expired magic link
    // (may need to set short TTL in test config or wait — or verify via direct DynamoDB TTL check)

    // Test 3: Used magic link (single-use)
    // 1. Complete flow once (gets JWT)
    // 2. Try same code again
    // 3. Assert: 401

    // Test 4: Token refresh
    // 1. Complete auth flow, get refresh token
    // 2. POST /api/auth/refresh with refresh token
    // 3. Assert: new JWT + new refresh token
    // 4. Old refresh token no longer works

    // Test 5: Logout
    // 1. Complete auth flow
    // 2. POST /api/auth/logout with refresh token
    // 3. Assert: 200
    // 4. Refresh with that token → 401

    // Test 6: Rate limiting
    // 1. Send 3 magic link requests for same email
    // 2. Assert: all succeed
    // 3. Send 4th request
    // 4. Assert: 429

    // Test 7: Kong JWT protection
    // 1. GET /api/users/me without token → 401
    // 2. Complete auth flow, get JWT
    // 3. GET /api/users/me with Bearer token → (200 or 404 or 503, but NOT 401)

    // Test 8: Auto-creation of new user on first login
    // 1. Use a never-before-seen email
    // 2. Complete auth flow
    // 3. Assert: IsNewUser = true in response
    // 4. Verify user record exists in DynamoDB (PK=USER#{id})
}
```

Also create `test/Snapp.Service.Auth.Tests/Snapp.Service.Auth.Tests.csproj` with references to:
- Snapp.TestHelpers
- Snapp.Shared
- xUnit
- FluentAssertions (for readable assertions)
- System.Net.Http.Json

If the auth service isn't deployed to Docker yet, create the tests so they:
- Call the API through Kong (http://localhost:8000/api/auth/...)
- Skip gracefully with `[Fact(Skip = "Auth service not deployed yet")]` if the service returns 503
- Include a comment: "Remove Skip attribute once Snapp.Service.Auth is deployed to Docker"

The tests should be structured so that when S2 implements the auth service and deploys it to Docker, these tests start passing without modification (just remove the Skip).
